qas.question: When did Elizabeth address the UN General Assembly?
What parliamentary session did Elizabeth open in 1957 while on tour?
On a tour to Ghana in 1961 what did Elizabeth dismiss as a fear?
In 1964 what was reported that Quebec extremists planned ?
In 1961 what was the first country Elizabeth made a state visit to?
In 1961 what was the last country Elizabeth made a state visit to?
In what year did President Kwame Nkrumah of Ghana replace Elizabeth as the head of state?
In what Canadian city is the Canadian Parliament?
In what year did Harold Macmillan die?

context: In <a0_0><b6_0>1957<b6_0/><a0_0/>, she made a state visit to the United States, where she addressed the United Nations General Assembly on behalf of the Commonwealth. On the same tour, she opened the <a1_0>23rd Canadian Parliament<a1_0/>, becoming the first monarch of Canada to open a parliamentary session. Two years later, solely in her capacity as Queen of Canada, she revisited the United States and toured Canada. In 1961, she toured Cyprus, <b4_0>India<b4_0/>, Pakistan, <b5_0>Nepal<b5_0/>, and Iran. On a visit to Ghana the same year, she dismissed fears for <a2_0>her safety<a2_0/>, even though her host, President Kwame Nkrumah, who had replaced her as head of state, was a target for assassins. Harold Macmillan wrote, "The Queen has been absolutely determined all through ... She is impatient of the attitude towards her to treat her as ... a film star ... She has indeed 'the heart and stomach of a man' ... She loves her duty and means to be a Queen." Before her tour through parts of Quebec in <b8_0>1964<b8_0/>, the press reported that extremists within the Quebec separatist movement were plotting <a3_0>Elizabeth's assassination<a3_0/>. No attempt was made, but a riot did break out while she was in <b7_0>Montreal<b7_0/>; the Queen's "calmness and courage in the face of the violence" was noted.
